## Passing std::vector to Functions

Passing a `std::vector` by value copies every element in the vector — an O(n) operation that silently tanks performance as the vector grows. The correct default is **pass by const reference**.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <numeric>
#include <vector>

double average(const std::vector<int>& v) {
    if (v.empty()) return 0.0;
    return static_cast<double>(std::accumulate(v.begin(), v.end(), 0))
           / static_cast<double>(v.size());
}

int main() {
    std::vector<int> scores { 88, 92, 75, 100, 63 };
    std::cout << average(scores) << '\n'; // 83.6
}
```

### When to use each parameter type

- `const std::vector<T>&` — the default. Read-only access, no copy. Use whenever the function doesn't need to modify the caller's vector.
- `std::vector<T>&` — non-const reference. Use when the function intentionally modifies the caller's vector (e.g., sorting in place, appending elements).
- `std::vector<T>` (by value) — use only when the function needs its own independent copy to mutate, and the caller must keep the original intact. Be explicit in a comment; it signals intent.

### Why copying is expensive

A `std::vector` owns heap memory. Copying it allocates a new heap block and copies every element. For a vector of a million `int`s that's ~4 MB of memory traffic on every call. A reference is just a pointer — one word, regardless of vector size.

### Returning vectors

Return by value freely. Named Return Value Optimization (NRVO) and mandatory copy elision (since C++17) mean the compiler constructs the returned vector directly in the caller's storage — no copy occurs in practice. Avoid returning `const std::vector<T>&` to a local variable; the local is destroyed when the function returns, leaving a dangling reference.

### The `std::size_t` subscript reminder

When iterating inside a receiving function, prefer a range-for loop or `std::size_t` loop index to avoid signed/unsigned comparison warnings — the same rule from the previous lesson applies inside function bodies too.

The rule is simple: **pass by `const` reference unless you have a specific reason not to.**

